Step 1 — Navigate to IAM:
      Go to AWS Console → Search for IAM
      In the left panel, click Roles → Click "Create Role"
Step 2 — Select Trusted Entity Type:
      Under Trusted Entity Type → Select AWS Service
Step 3 — Select Use Case:
      Under Service or Use Case → Search and Select EC2
      Under Use Case → Select EC2 → Click Next
Step 4 — Attach Permission Policies:
      In the Permission Policies search bar, 
      search for: AmazonEC2ReadOnlyAccess
      Check the box to attach the Read Only Access policy → Click Next
Step 5 — Name the Role:
      Under Role Name, enter:  DemoRoleEC2Instance
      Review the details → Click "Create Role"

✅ Result:
A new IAM Role DemoRoleEC2Instance is created with:
Trusted Entity: AWS Service (EC2)
Permission: EC2 Read Only Access


Example:
Sometimes AWS Services need to do things on your behalf
But they need permission to do so!

Real Life Example:
You hire a driver (EC2 Instance)
Driver needs to access your garage (AWS Services)
You give driver a KEY (IAM Role) to access garage
Driver can now access garage on your behalf 
